The DP[i][j] represents the minimum number of moves to reach position (i,j) and merge all chips up to that point. But wait, maybe the DP is tracking the cumulative cost up to column i, considering whether we end up in row 1 or 2. The dynamic programming part seems a bit tricky. Let's analyze the transitions. For each column i from l to r, the code calculates dp[i][1] and dp[i][2]. The transitions are:

dp[i][1] = min(dp[i-1][1] + s[i][2], dp[i-1][2] + 1) + 1;
dp[i][2] = min(dp[i-1][1] + 1, dp[i-1][2] + s[i][1]) + 1;

Hmm. Let's think. When moving to row 1 at column i, the cost could come from either the previous row 1 or row 2. If previous was row 1, then adding s[i][2] (which is 1 if there's a chip in row 2 of column i). Then, the min between those two options. Then adding 1. Not sure why.
